The Strandline Compact made Mafdet a city rather than a collection of competing factions.
Its genius was recognizing that wardens need guild throughput, guilds need ledger legitimacy, ledgers need warden enforcement — encoding that as constitutional law.
Written under Fracture Era pressure, its veto provisions reflect lessons from attempted bloc dominance during drafting.
The Harbor Wardens' bloc includes the Quay Concord's senior captains as informal participants, giving maritime experience direct input into Compact decisions.
The Ledger Houses bloc includes the Red Sand Accounts — its debt conversion tactics strain the "harbor first" principle while remaining within Compact norms.
The Sand-Sea Carters' Guild holds the most territory of any Compact institution; the Saltglass Reach cairn system is a quasi-judicial zone where Guild authority supplements civil law.
Compact disputes are resolved by Shrine adjudicators applying the "harbor first, dual attestation, swift judgment" sequence as a priority ladder.

